    longDescription: "A foundation is not a commodity. It is the single most consequential structural decision made in the life of any building, and in Seattle, the geological and environmental variables that govern a foundation's long-term performance are more complex than in almost any other major American city. At Cloud Concrete of Seattle, our structural team approaches every foundation project with the rigor and precision the work demands, because we understand that everything built above grade is only as reliable as the concrete we pour below it.\n\nSeattle's subsurface geology is the first challenge every foundation contractor in this city must confront honestly. The region sits on a layered combination of glacial till, marine clay, loose sand, and in some low-lying areas near the waterfront and South Lake Union, historic fill material that can be highly unpredictable under load. Glacial till, the dense, compacted material left behind by the retreating Vashon glacier, is an excellent bearing surface when you can reach it. The problem is that it is often overlain by expansive clay layers that swell significantly when saturated and contract when dry, creating the cyclical heave-and-settle movement that damages foundations over decades. Our process always begins with a review of available geotechnical data for the site and, when warranted, we recommend a formal soil report before committing to a foundation design.\n\nSeattle's seismic environment adds another layer of engineering complexity. The Pacific Northwest sits atop the Cascadia Subduction Zone, one of the most significant seismic hazards in North America. The City of Seattle's building codes reflect this reality, requiring specific reinforcement standards for all new foundations and structural slabs. Our team designs and pours foundations in full compliance with the current Seattle Building Code and the International Building Code, incorporating the required rebar schedules, anchor bolt specifications, and connection hardware that ensure the structure above can move with seismic forces rather than fracturing at the base.\n\nFor residential projects, we handle the full range of foundation types that Seattle's varied housing stock requires. Continuous perimeter stem walls are the standard for new wood-frame construction, poured to a depth below the frost line with a level top plate for framing attachment. Monolithic slabs, where the thickened edge and interior slab are poured as a single unit, are used for ADUs, garage additions, and additions where the site conditions support it. Crawl space foundations require careful attention to vapor barriers and foundation vents to manage the chronic moisture issue that plagues countless older Seattle homes, where inadequate original moisture management has led to wood rot and mold in the structural framing above.\n\nEvery foundation we pour receives a minimum 4,000 PSI concrete mix with the appropriate admixtures for the pour conditions, whether that means accelerators for cold weather pours in winter or retarders for large continuous pours in summer to prevent premature set. We install a minimum 6-mil vapor barrier beneath all ground-contact slabs and integrate drainage mat systems against basement walls where hydrostatic pressure is a concern. Form work is checked for level and plumb before every pour, because a foundation that comes out of the ground a quarter-inch out of level creates cascading problems for every trade that follows.\n\nIf you are planning a home addition, building a new ADU in your backyard, or need to address an existing foundation issue, call Cloud Concrete of Seattle at (206) 495-0997 for a consultation. We will assess your site, review any available soil data, and provide a foundation design recommendation that meets code, suits your soil, and gives the structure above it the stable, durable base it deserves.",
